data.name: label2.Text
data.value: Dogs shake their heads for several reasons, with the primary one being to remove irritants or moisture from their ears. This instinctual behavior helps dislodge dirt, water, insects, or other debris that may have entered their ear canal, potentially causing discomfort or irritation. Additionally, dogs may shake their heads as a response to itching or irritation caused by allergies, ear infections, or skin conditions. By vigorously shaking their heads, dogs attempt to alleviate discomfort and restore balance to their sensory organs. While occasional head shaking is normal and serves a practical purpose, persistent or excessive shaking could indicate an underlying health issue, and it's essential for pet owners to monitor their dog's behavior and seek veterinary attention if necessary.
